    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="625"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d625">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/932</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 18, 1918</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 1.24 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4704. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 2122. Embassy’s 4331 of December 5, our 2001;<note n="1" xml:id="d625fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> Embassy’s 4423 of December 9, our 2024;<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d625fn2">Not printed.</note> and Embassy’s 4648 of December 16, our
                        2104.<note n="1" xml:id="d625fn3">Not printed.</note> N.O.T. agreement has
                    just been signed by representatives of British, French and Italian Governments
                    and N.O.T., although all parties greatly regretted that no answer from War Trade
                    Board has been received to our 2001 which was sent from here 13 days ago, yet as
                    Valstar must leave for Holland this morning and as British representatives are
                    to leave for Paris tomorrow negotiations could not be further prolonged here and
                    for the reasons indicated in our above tables it was considered undesirable to
                    leave negotiations in an uncompleted state with probable result that they would
                    be entirely reopened by Dutch Government or N.O.T. at The Hague. …</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
